  "coalition_shifts": [
    {
      "friction_rebinds": "Training friction binds on enterprise absorption and labor-retraining politics; drug discovery friction binds on FDA pathway, wet-lab throughput, and IP structure. Moving compute-hours from fine-tuning pipelines to target discovery shifts the blocker from HR departments to regulators and CROs --- a harder but cleaner fight because the regulator has a suffering mandate on paper. Harm trade is small and real: you lose some worker-retraining capacity (norm_workers_dignity takes a marginal hit) but the destination's DALY math dominates by an order of magnitude. Not a scoring artifact.",
      "from_intervention_id": "intv_training",
      "gaining_camps": [
        "camp_global_health",
        "camp_biomedical",
        "camp_anthropic"
      ],
      "losing_camps": [
        "camp_displaced_workers"
      ],
      "to_intervention_id": "intv_drug_discovery"
    },
    {
      "friction_rebinds": "Grid friction is physical --- interconnect queues, transformer lead times, NIMBY. Drug discovery friction is institutional --- trial design, regulatory approval, manufacturing. The +0.267 harm_robustness delta is the honest signal here: drug discovery doesn't pour concrete or burn gas. The catch is that grid was enabling infrastructure for every compute-intensive downstream including drug discovery itself, so the move is only coherent if you're reallocating effort (researcher-hours, capital allocation attention), not electrons. If the operator reads this as 'stop building grid capacity,' that's the scoring artifact --- grid is a substrate, not a competitor.",
      "from_intervention_id": "intv_grid",
      "gaining_camps": [
        "camp_global_health",
        "camp_biomedical",
        "camp_animal_welfare"
      ],
      "losing_camps": [
        "camp_palantir",
        "camp_anthropic"
      ],
      "to_intervention_id": "intv_drug_discovery"
    },
    {
      "friction_rebinds": "Alt protein friction binds on consumer adoption, price parity, and ag-industry lobbying; drug discovery friction binds on regulatory pathway and clinical trials. The trade is real, not an artifact: animal welfare loses its single largest numerator lever (factory farming scale) for a human-DALY gain. This pair is exactly the kind of cross-species suffering-weighting fight that the composite can't resolve --- if you weight animal suffering at 1:1 with human the delta_net flips. Operator's default weighting pushes toward the move; the blindspot is that the weighting is a normative choice, not a fact.",
      "from_intervention_id": "intv_alt_protein",
      "gaining_camps": [
        "camp_global_health",
        "camp_biomedical"
      ],
      "losing_camps": [
        "camp_animal_welfare"
      ],
      "to_intervention_id": "intv_drug_discovery"
    },
    {
      "friction_rebinds": "Compute friction is capex and power; drug discovery friction is regulatory and wet-lab. The +0.450 harm_robustness jump is the dominant term --- compute buildout is the dirtiest line item in the whole graph (power draw, concentration, dual-use). Xrisk gains because less frontier compute means less capability overhang; displaced workers gain because compute expansion is the substrate of the labor-displacement trajectory. Harm trade is robust across axioms: Kantian, capabilities, and aggregate-welfare frames all prefer the destination. Not a scoring artifact.",
      "from_intervention_id": "intv_compute",
      "gaining_camps": [
        "camp_global_health",
        "camp_biomedical",
        "camp_xrisk",
        "camp_displaced_workers"
      ],
      "losing_camps": [
        "camp_palantir",
        "camp_anthropic"
      ],
      "to_intervention_id": "intv_drug_discovery"
    },
    {
      "friction_rebinds": "Alignment friction is conceptual --- we don't know what we're doing yet --- and drug discovery friction is procedural, which is why the viability delta is negative (-0.101): you're moving from a field with low throughput-per-researcher to one with queue-bound throughput. The -0.033 harm_robustness delta understates the real cost: alignment research is an option premium on catastrophic tail risk, and its suffering numerator is near-zero by design (it's insurance, not intervention). The composite can't price options. This is the pair where the deterministic delta is most suspect.",
      "from_intervention_id": "intv_alignment_research",
      "gaining_camps": [
        "camp_global_health",
        "camp_biomedical"
      ],
      "losing_camps": [
        "camp_xrisk",
        "camp_anthropic"
      ],
      "to_intervention_id": "intv_drug_discovery"
    }
  ],
